    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1309129342" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1309129342" />
    <a title="PattyMacDotComma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1128612-pattymacdotcomma"><img alt="PattyMacDotComma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577835191p2/1128612.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1309129342?book_show_action=true">Aug 31, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="PattyMacDotComma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="PattyMacDotComma" href="/user/show/1128612-pattymacdotcomma">PattyMacDotComma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=fiction-adult">fiction-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=aa">aa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=aa-col">aa-col</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=kindle">kindle</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1128612-pattymacdotcomma?shelf=bio-memoir">bio-memoir</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1309129342" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11449654128128016323"><b>5★<br/>“Everything struggles to live. Look at that tree growing up there out of that grating. It gets no sun, and water only when it rains. It&apos;s growing out of sour earth. And it&apos;s strong because its hard struggle to live is making it strong. My children will be strong that way.&quot;</b><br/><br/>That is Katie’s rebuttal to ‘friends’ who told her that Francie was such a sickly baby that it would be for the best if she died. Little did they know what strength of character Katie had and Francie developed. It’s a terrifi</span>
  <span id="freeText11449654128128016323" style="display:none"><b>5★<br />“Everything struggles to live. Look at that tree growing up there out of that grating. It gets no sun, and water only when it rains. It's growing out of sour earth. And it's strong because its hard struggle to live is making it strong. My children will be strong that way."</b><br /><br />That is Katie’s rebuttal to ‘friends’ who told her that Francie was such a sickly baby that it would be for the best if she died. Little did they know what strength of character Katie had and Francie developed. It’s a terrific story, and I’m sure there’s nothing I can add by way of comment other than to reintroduce it to anyone who hasn’t heard of this classic.<br /><br />Written in 1934, it has been a favourite of many readers for decades. The criticism I have read is often that it is depressing, so why did anyone bother to write it? My criticism is that it was not written as the memoir that it actually was. I think if it had been, people might have been more forgiving of the descriptions of poverty and suffering and injustice.<br /><br />Anna Quindlen, in her foreword to this edition, wrote:<br /><br /><b>“There is no doubt that this is an autobiographical story; originally written as memoir, it was reconfigured as fiction at the request of an editor at its publishing house. Smith herself, describing the deluge of reader letters that accompanied both the initial publication of Tree and its subsequent editions, wrote, <i>‘One fifth of my letters start out “Dear Francie.'</i>"</b><br /><br />I was reminded often of <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/252577.Angela_s_Ashes__Frank_McCourt___1_" title="Angela's Ashes (Frank McCourt, #1) by Frank McCourt" rel="nofollow noopener">Angela's Ashes</a>, which was written as a memoir and was an even more harrowing tale of growing up in depression-era Brooklyn in abject destitution and misery. In both cases, the children survived to become renowned authors. <br /><br />Katie married at 17 to Jimmy Nolan, an entertaining, good-looking fellow and the love of her life. He caught her eye and she plotted until she caught his. She was pretty and determined, and they had quite a love story over the years. But the book begins in 1912, when Francie is 11, and it’s Francie who tells us their history and hers.<br /><br />This is just before WW1 is beginning, so there is worry about whether America will become involved, who will have to go to fight. Katie’s parents are German immigrants, which just exacerbates the difficulties. Her father was a tyrant as she was growing up, and it’s amazing she came through as upbeat as she did.<br /><br />Francie and her older sister and younger brother do whatever they can to earn a few pennies, and they run errands constantly to get a bone from the butcher or bread and a bit of condensed milk. They live on bread, and I’ll include a long “recipe” section at the end to show how creative Katie was. It's no wonder that the occasional pickle or bit of sweet features so strongly in her story.<br /><br />When food supplies are really low, Katie and the children pretend they are explorers, waiting to be rescued while being lost in a blizzard on their way to the North Pole. She cleans houses to make up for Jimmy’s meagre earnings as a singer and has dreams for her kids. <br /><br />Francie has inherited her mother’s determination, and it is such a delight to see her figure out how to get to a better school to get a better education and stretch her boundaries. She loves stories and books and vows to read a book a day for the rest of her life. As for her approach to mathematics, I’ll include another long quotation at the end. I loved the whole idea!<br /><br />Katie’s sister Sissy, is a favourite – a colourful auntie who loves the boys, the boys love her and she is always in some kind of trouble. She’s the classic heart-of-gold pretty girl who is too easy for her own good. <br /><br />Yes, it’s a hard book to read if you’re easily distressed by poverty. So many tales of suffering now are written about the great wars and the Holocaust, but this was just everyday life among the very poor. These could be families from Dickens. There is joy and celebration as well.<br /><br />This is not Poverty Porn, this is HISTORY. This is what life was like for this family, and it’s well-told and uplifting in so many ways. These days, I’m sure they’d be homeless and at even greater risk for their lives. <br /><br />I loved it. Below are the long quotations.<br /><br />Here are Katie’s recipes:<br /><br /><b>“The Nolans practically lived on that stale bread and what amazing things Katie could make from it! She'd take a loaf of stale bread, pour boiling water over it, work it up into a paste, flavor it with salt, pepper, thyme, minced onion and an egg (if eggs were cheap), and bake it in the oven. When it was good and brown, she made a sauce from half a cup of ketchup, two cups of boiling water, seasoning, a dash of strong coffee, thickened it with flour and poured it over the baked stuff. It was good, hot, tasty and staying. What was left over, was sliced thin the next day and fried in hot bacon fat.<br /><br />Mama made a very fine bread pudding from slices of stale bread, sugar, cinnamon and a penny apple sliced thin. When this was baked brown, sugar was melted and poured over the top. Sometimes she made what she had named <i>Weg Geschnissen</i>, which laboriously translated meant something made with bread bits that usually would be thrown away. Bits of bread were dipped into a batter made from flour, water, salt and an egg and then fried in deep hot fat. While they were frying, Francie ran down to the candy store and bought a penny's worth of brown rock candy. This was crushed with a rolling pin and sprinkled on top of the fried bits just before eating. The crystals didn't quite melt and that made it wonderful.<br /><br />Saturday supper was a red-letter meal. The Nolans had fried meat! A loaf of stale bread was made into pulp with hot water and mixed with a dime 's worth of chopped meat into which an onion had been cleavered. Salt and a penny's worth of minced parsley were added for flavor. This was made up into little balls, fried and served with hot ketchup.”</b><br /><br />And here is how Francie visualises mathematics:<br /><br /><b>“ She devised a game in which each number was a family member and the "answer" made a family grouping with a story to it. Naught was a babe in arms. He gave no trouble. Whenever he appeared you just "carried" him. The figure 1 was a pretty baby girl just learning to walk, and easy to handle; 2 was a baby boy who could walk and talk a little. He went into family Hfe (into sums, etc.) with very little trouble. And 3 was an older boy in kindergarten, who had to be watched a little. Then there was 4, a girl of Francie's age. She was almost as easy to "mind" as 2. The mother was 5, gentle and kind. In large sums, she came along and made everything easy the way a mother should. The father, 6, was harder than the others but very just. But 7 was mean. He was a crotchety old grandfather and not at all accountable for how he came out. The grandmother, 8, was hard too, but easier to understand than 7. Hardest of all was 9. He was company and what a hard time fitting <i>him</i> into family life!<br /><br />When Francie added a sum, she would fix a little story to go with the result. If the answer was 924, it meant that the litde boy and girl were being minded by company while the rest of the family went out. When a number such as 1024 appeared, it meant that all the little children were playing together in the yard. The number 62 meant that papa was taking the little boy for a walk; 50 meant that mama had the baby out in the buggy for an airing and 78 meant grandfather and grandmother sitting home by the fire of a winter's evening. Each single combination of numbers was a new set-up for the family and no two stories were ever the same.<br /><br />Francie took the game with her up into algebra. X was the boy's sweetheart who came into the family life and complicated it. Y was the boy friend who caused trouble. So arithmetic was a warm and human thing to Francie and occupied many lonely hours of her time.”</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="11449654128128016323" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


